html.htmlText:
Uber close to Universal Studios.
Enjoy the Amazing views and hike to the Hollywood Sign and Lake Hollywood. This home has a community atmosphere with other Airbnb guests in different rooms. It's a great place to meet like-minded people or enjoy complete privacy in your room. There are 2 bathrooms shared between 2 rooms.

** Please take a look at the note at the end, regarding NEW Airbnb rules.

This listing is for 1 bedroom in my 3-bedroom home. 2 bathrooms are shared, just like at a regular house. You will get a key to the lock on your door. The 1st large bathroom is across the hall from your bedroom. A 2nd bathroom is in the front of the house. You have a desk, chair, and a large Smart TV with access to all the streaming services.
The essential rules in this community house are being friendly, kind, and respectful. There are often guests staying in the other rooms.
I have a small dog: Chiquita is a 12 lb. Chihuahua mix that is nine years old. She loves sitting next to you and getting treats and petted.

**Why are you paying more to stay than in the past? Taxes.
The City of Los Angeles has made new rules. Guests now pay taxes into the city coffers. These are the fees you see added to your total payment. Hotels chains complained to the City of LA that Airbnb was stealing their business by offering less expensive rates. New city rules mean no host can offer an Airbnb to guests unless the host lives on the property. This is why you see shared spaces. The city shut down 30 thousand properties. I believe this hurts tourism, but you can't fight city hall. Thank you for supporting small businesses like mine. I truly appreciate you.

Guests have access to the Living room, Kitchen, Laundry room, and Backyard.
The Chef's kitchen was custom designed by an LA celebrity chef. It is new and big. You can use the ENTIRE kitchen with all its gadgets, tools, pots, baking pans, and spices. You will be given space to store your groceries in the refrigerator and pantry. Laundry machines are on the premises for you to use.

I work from my home office and am available for any questions you may have.  I respect my guest's privacy and want them to have whatever they need to make their visit here the best experience it can be.

section.houseRulesSubtitle: You'll be staying in someone's home, so please treat it with care and respect.

html.htmlText:
Before I welcome you into my home, I would like to know a little about you and your visit to Southern California.    If your profile doesn't have an accurate picture of yourself, please send me one. 
The most important rules on my property are being friendly, considerate, and kind.  No outside visitors without my permission first.  Smoking is ONLY allowed in the backyard, where you can enjoy the view too—absolutely NO smoking or vaping inside the house. 
 No wild partying.  No Drugs.  No hair dyeing on-premises without permission.  No candles with an open flame unless I provide them.  If you are having trouble with your cell phone signal indoors, use the backyard: you can get a strong signal from there.   
Please be considerate of my neighbors while here.  Airbnb has had a lot of negative media attention because of party houses and inconsiderate visitors in local neighborhoods.  While here, remember you are always: "a friend of Helen's," and your behavior is a reflection on me.

section.about:
I hate hotel chains.  I have enjoyed becoming a veteran host on Airbnb, having hosted over 2000 guests in my home since 2013, many of them returning again and again. I have learned many new things from my guests that have made my life richer: things about their hometown, recipes, new websites.
I am of Indian descent; my parents immigrated to the US from Kerala in South India, and I am a native Angeleno.  My hobby is collecting "old" technology. I find it fascinating how quickly technology is changing.  I have a 1950 television, an antique record player, a camera, a telegraph machine, and a telephone in my collection. My favorite food is dark chocolate-- I have to have a bite a day! I love being a tourist in my own city, exploring all the unique spots that most residents take for granted and never visit.  Things that irritate me when I travel are: getting lost and people that ruin my day with their not-friendly attitudes. Little details matter and I love making that difference for my guests.  I have worked as a tour guide, so I can give you those helpful hints that can make a huge difference when traveling.
